{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_noone_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060026A/1930020701/0133.xml":{"full_text":"A-4\nFEDERAL RESERVE\nACHIEVKO6JECI\n'Reduction iri Rediscount Rate\nt Seen as Factor Toward\nStability.\nBT DAVID LAWRENCE.\ni Stability in money rates\u2014the objective\nfcf the Federal Reserve system for sev\neral months \u2014appears at last to have\nbeen achieved.\nWhen the stock market collapse came\nlast October, there were predictions of\nhow low money rates would stimulate\nconstruction and business activity as\na (?alnst the long period of high rates\n\u25a0which had throttled business in many\nfields. But low money did not come\nAnd while there were days of compara\ntive ease in the money market, the\nfluctuations produced uncertainty. The\nmovement of gold abroad caused some\nconcern. And the real estate first mort\ngage market of the country showed a\nlittle improvement.\nOne of the first things Treasury\nofficials said when the market collapsed\nwas that the biggest single item in a\nbusiness revival would be lower money\nTates or rather \u201ccheap money.\u201d\nHesitate Over Lower Rate.\nThe Federal Reserve Banks did reduce\ntheir rediscount rate and this was a\nsign of the direction in which money\nTates were moving, but when there was\na hesitancy a week or two ago to bring\nthe discount rate down further there\nwas some corroboration of the idea that\nfluctuations had not ended and that\nmoney rates might rise again.\nThe action of the Federal Re\nserve Bank in reducing the redis\ncount rate on Thursday to 4 per\ncent, which or course had the approval\nof the Federal Reserve Board here, was\nthat the authorities decided money\nrates could go down still further. The\nfact that money in the call market\nwas renewing around 4 per cent, with\na tendency to go down below that, had\nits effect, but at the same time the\ndrop in the rate of bankers\u2019 acceptances\nproved a decisive factor too, for at last\nthe bill pollcv of the Federal Reserve\nBoard, begun last Summer, is having its\n.maximum influence. Control of money\nrates through the regulation of rates\nion bills has long been agitated as one\nms the functions of the reserve system.\nThe bill or banker\u2019s acceptance, having\nthe indorsement of two or more banks,\nis considered even better security at\nthe Federal Reserve than prime com\nmercial paper or collateral loans. Hence\nas the bill rate goes down because of\nthe demand for such acceptances, the\nrediscount rate is supposed to come\ndown too, so that the two may keep a\ncertain margin between them.\nIt was when the bill rate was higher\nthan the rediscount rate last year that\nthe climax came and a high rediscount\nrate was finally established after a\nprolonged argument between the Fed\neral Reserve Bany directors of New York\nand the board here.\nAbsolute Agreement.\nNow there is absolute agreement on\nihow money rates should be handled, and\nthe drop in the rediscount rate at New\nYork may be expected to be the fore\nrunner of 4 per cent rates in other\nFederal Reserve districts. It is still\ndoubtful whether the rate will ever go\nback to 3*/ 2 per cent, which was the\nbeginning of the so-called Coolidge\nboom, but it Is much more likely to go\ndown than up igain. The 4 per cent\nis considered a medium rate around\n\u25a0which the other mqpey influences can\nrevolve with confidence. A 4 per cent\nrediscount rate means a better market\nfor bonds and the financing of the con\nstruction activities of the country\nthrough building loans. It is a sign\nof a decided improvement in industry\nand a favorable outlook in business,\necdmicht. 1830.)\nDAPPER BANDITS ROB\nJAMES FEED COMPANY\nYouthful Fair Brandish Revolvers,\nEmpty Cash Drawer and\nMake Escape.\nTwo dapper young men who are\nbelieved to have a long series of daring\nstore hold-ups in Washington during\nthe last two or three months entered\nthe feed store of James Son Co., 306\nTenth street, last evening just before\nclosing time and, brandishing revolvers,\nlooted the cash register.\nWilliam James, head of the company,\nwas preparing to close the doors when\nthe two unmasked men walked in, drew\nrevolvers, and cautioned him not to\nmake an outcry. The proprietor told\nHeadquarters Detective Thomas Nalle\nand C. W. Mansfield that the pair\nforced him behind a counter and made\nhim open the cash drawer. It contained\nonly $3. They took this, ran through\nthe open door and disappeared.\n\nCAPITOL EMPLOYE DIES.\nTrank A. Byron, Colored, Held in\nHigh Esteem.\nFrank A. Byron, colored, 58 years old,\none of the most highly esteemed and\nefficient employes at the Capitol, died\nthis morning in Freedmen\u2019s Hospital\nafter suffering a stroke of apoplexy.\nByron, whose home was in Chicago,\nhad been a clerk at the Capitol for 29\nyears and had for many years served\nas clerk to the House committee on\nnaval affairs, having been appointed\nfirst by Representative Foss of Illinois\nand more recently .under Chairman But\nler of Pennsylvania and Chairman Brit\nten of Illinois. He was married and is\nsurvived by a wife, daughter and\nbrother.\n\nKoelliker Asks Divorce.\nAbsolute divorce is asked in a suit\nfiled in the District Supreme Court by\nWilliam G. Koelliker, a member of the\nArmy Band at the War College, against\nMargaret Koelliker, who resides at\nCleveland, Ohio. A resident of the\nOhio town is named as co-respondent.\nHe says he was married March 29. 1926,\nand in the following May, he declared,\nhis wife was ccnvicted in Juvenile Court\nat Cleveland oi a statutory charge. The\nhusband is represented by Attorneys\nToomey Toomey.\nOne of the attractions at Cannes.\nFrance, is a woman who lives on ground\nglass in a glass cage.\nI GREATEST JT\nUsed car sale\nJ.N\nChevrolet History\nSEE Ol KISMAN ADV. PAGE 18-A\nGARAGES\nTIN ROOFS\nPORCHES' BUILT\nWE BUILD, KEBI li.D. BEMODEL.\nREPAIB ANYTHING\nCONSTRUCTION\nTEXAN\u2019S DAILY GAME WITH \"BOYS\u201d\nLETS THEM \"EARN A NICKEL\u201d\ni\n\nI\ni\n\ni\nREPRESENTATIVE JOSEPH JEFFERSON MANSFIELD.\nBy the Associated Press.\nThere\u2019s a little game that dally goes\non In the marble-floored lobby of the\nHouse of Representatives.\nLike a mounted captain of the Texas\nvolunteer guards that he used to com\nmand, Joseph Jefferson Mansfield, wheel\nchair member of Congress from the\nninth Texas district, comes charging\ninto the lobby.\nSternly he speaks to whatever col\nleague happens to be handy:\n\u201cBoy, boy, want to earn another\nnickel? Open the gate.\u201d\nWill Rogers\nSays:\nNEW YORK CITY \u2014Arrived from\nyour old-time county seat today, and\nfor a country that has no tradition\nor background you are not bad.\nHave read all your papers today on\nthe conference, and here is one\nthing they seem to overlook that i\nreally makes this thing harder than\nyou think. You must remember that\nit\u2019s national pride that they are\njuggling with. There is far more\npride involved at this conference\nthan ships. The minute you rate a\nnation they naturally think you are\nestablishing their Importance In\ncomparison to everybody else. Na\ntions don\u2019t mind being amall, but\nthey don\u2019t want it advertised to the\nworld. So, remember It\u2019s not ton\nnage they.are prorating; It\u2019s prestige.\nIf they 'ofily had to divide up ships\nthey would be' home next week.\n(Copyright. ino.)\nFRCERS.\ni\nOfficers for the ensuing year ver* I\nnominated last night at a meeting c'\nthe Washington Hairdressers and Cos-\naetologists\u2019 Association In the Hamil\nton Hotel. The officers will be elected\nMarch 6. They are:\nPresident, Emile Beauvais; vioe pres\nident, Charles H. Powers; secretary,\nCarry Quinn; financial secretary, Mrs.\nJulia Crandall; treasurer. Miss Cath\nerine Lee Ogilvie; chairman nominating\ncommittee. Carry Quinn; entertain\nment committee, Samuel Lidoss, and\neducation and standards committee,\nArthur S. Dillon.\n(WYTHE BOYS\" SMQP/W)\nPre-Inventory Sale 5\noffers many things your young\nsters need\u2014the prices of which\nhave been cut to the \u201cquick.\u201d\n2-Knicker Suits\nS2O to $25 Grades\n$lO-75\nMostly fancy patterns; a few plain blue serges.\nAbout 70 suits in the combined lots. Sizes 6to\n17 years.\nAll Boys Fancy Suits and Overcoats are\nunder \u201cclearance orders\u201d\u2014choose as you will\nBoys\u2019 Lumberjacks\nWool, Suede and Corduroy\n$3.95 grade $325\n$6.00 grade $4.25\n$7 and $8.50 grades $5.25\nsl2 and $13.50 grades .$8.75\nBoys\u2019 Winter Union Suits 20% Off\nPopular makes \u2014Duofold and Augusta\nBoys\u2019 $1 Neckwear 79c\nBoys\u2019 $1.50 and $1.95 Wool Golf Hose.... sl-15\nSecond Floor.\nThe Avenue at Ninth\nTHE EVENING STAB. WASHINGTON. D. C., FRIDAY. FEBRITABY 7, 1930.\nAll the Representatives are glad to\nbe boys again for Mansfield.\nThey push aside the swinging doors,\nand Mansfield swiftly wheels himself\nthrough to the floor of the House. All\nthe vitality bespoken by his upstanding\nshock of gray hair, hLs bristling gray\nmustache, goes into the motion with\nwhich the Texas Representative propels\nhis wheel chair. His is always the\nfarthest front seat. He sits erectly and\nalertly listens to debate or animatedly\nchats with hLs colleagues on the front\nrow\u2014behind his wheel chair.\nWhenever he appears he is greeted\nwith a gay, \u201cHello, there, judge.\u201d\nThen it\u2019s: \u201cBoy, boy, want to earn\nanother nickel? Open the gate.\u201d\nHOUSE PLANS BIGGER\nCEREMONY FEBRUARY 22\nTilson Confers With G. O. F. Steer\ning Committee on Washington\nBirthday Observance.\nHouse Leader Tilson held a confer\nence this morning with the Republican\nsteering committee, at which plans were\ndiscussed for a more elaborate cere\nmony in the House than usual on\nWashington\u2019s birthday, February 22.\nThe reason for the more impressive\nceremony Is to call Nation-wide at\ntention to plans being worked out by\na commission appointed by former\nPresident Coolidge under an act of\nCongress for a big celebration of the\n200th anniversary of Washington\u2019s\nbirth hi 1932.\nFollowing the conference House Lead\ner Tilson said that he expects that the\nceremony In the House on Washing\nton's birthday this year will be one\nof the most Impressive events ever held\nin the chamber. It is probable that\nthe** exercises wl h be broadcast over\nIt Nation-wide hook-up.\nBankruptcy is asked.\nTowers Heating Company Files\nD. C. Court Application.\nThe Towers Heating Co., 917 New\nYork avenue, has filed an application in\nthe District Supreme Court to be ad\njudged bankrupt. The company will\nfile later its schedule of assets and lia\nbilities. Ford Powers, is president and\nacting treasurer of the company, and\nWilliam H. Towers is secretary. Attor\nney Richard A. Harman filed the pe\ntition.\nSENATE REJECTS\nWHITELEAD CUT\nj Tariff Reduction From 2 1-2\nto 2 Cents a Pound Lost,\n37-35.\n\nBy the Associated Press,\nj The Senate today disapproved a re\nduction in the present tariff on white\nlead used in the manufacture of paints\nfrom 2 1 6 to 2 cents a pound.\nSenator Couzens, Republican, Michi\ngan, asserted after the vote on white\nlead that he was not a \u201csky high pro\ntectionist nor a free trader\u201d but he did\nnot propose to vote for reductions,\nregardless of their merits, without the\nproducers having been heard.\nAll the rates acted upon were left\nundisturbed in the pending bill and\nHouse measure and Couzens said they\nwere not even discussed in committee\nhearings.\nTen Republicans and 27 Democrats\nvoted for the white lead duty reduction,\nwhile three Democrats, Broussard,\nLouisiana; Thomas, Oklahoma, and\nTrammel, Florida, Joined 35 Republi\ncans against it.\nDemocrats started on another tarlff\nj slashing drive today, winning by 37 to\nI 35 a reduction in the present duty on\nred lead, from 2% to 2% cents a pound.\nSenator Harrison, Democrat, Missis\nsippi, proposed the reduction. Previous\nly his forces, supported by the Repub\ni llcan Independents, had accomplished\ni a cut in the rate on litharge, a lead\ni pigment used in the manufacture of\nglass and pottery, from 2*/ 2 to 2\\i\nj cents a pound. No record vote was\ntaken on this amendment,\nj Harrison contended the imports of\nred lead, used in the manufacture of\npreservative paints, were negligible.\nSenator Bingham, Republican, Con\nnecticut, warned against lowering pres\nent rates on the ground It would be\nharmful to business.\n\u201cI do not think we have any mandate\nto lower the 1922 rates and hurt Ameri\ncan business,\u201d he asserted.\nHarrison started another argument\nbetween the Democrats and Republican\nindependents on the one hand and ad\nmlnLstration Republicans on the other\nwhen he proposed another cut in the\npresent levy on white lead, used In the\nmanufacture of exterior paints, from\n2*6 to 2 cents a pound. He asserted\nthit exports in 1928 were 13,000,000\npounds and said a true compensatory\nlevy would be less than 2 cents.\nK\nWU^K.\nIk\n\n|Bl. |^^HHHH\u00a3j|fl\nURNITURE is not only a necessary\nm background in our scheme of home Lm|^^Hhh\nlife, but is also an outstanding feature in the\nadvertising columns of THE STAR. More\nso right now, possibly, because this is Feb\nruary, and February is synonymous with\ni\nfurniture. We feel that the real reason THE\nSTAR prints more furniture advertising\nthan all the other Washington papers com\nbined is because THE STAR is eagerly read\nby the women who preside over the more\nthan 100,000 homes in which THE STAR is\nreceived every day in the year.\n\n%\\\\z J\u00a3kf.\nEvery Day and Every Sunday\nTHE GREAT NEWSPAPER OF THE NATION\u2019S CAPITAL\n1\nMechanio If Killed in Crash.\nNASHVILLE, Tenn., February 7 <JP).\nInjured In an airplane crash late yes\n\u2014So We Started All\nOver Again\u201d ill\nI! !*-i'\nI p!\nu Things didn't always look g\nso bright. There was a time\nwhen John and I were worried.\nWe were hopelessly in debt and i|\nconstantly annoyed by insistent g\ncreditors. Then John worked\nout his problem by cleaning up I\nhis debts zvith a Morris Plan\nloan. We started with a clean i\nslate and have established our- J\nselves by saving up a little each i|\nzveek.\u201d\nAlmost every day zee receive com-\nM merits such as this from thankful jsl\nindividuals who have availed them\nia selves of the services of this institu- i|\nJB tion. M\nill\n1 MORRIS PLAN BANK 3|\nUnder Supervision U.\u2018 S. Treasury\nterday, W. Noble Kirkland, aviation\nmechanic, died soon afterward at a\nhospital. The pilot of the plane, Ches\nter Borum, was seriously hurt.\nftii'N ifCTsTaYiWdaK.y;\nJ p\nPre-Inventory\u2019s Offerings\nAre of pre-eminent importance\n\u2014cutting ruthlessly to achieve\nclearance \u2014a rule of the P-B store\nP-B Overcoats\nIn two groups\u2014\n$9*7.50\n$35 and S4O grades\n$^7.50\n$45, SSO, S6O and $65 grades.\nThird Floor.\ni P-B Suits\nMost of them have two pairs of trousers.\n$35, S4O and $45 grades.-.\n$45, SSO, $55 and S6O grades.\nStreet Floor.\nIt's all P-B clothing which means\napproved styles, exclusive patterns and\nstandard qualities.\nThe Avenue at Ninth","height":"25365","width":"19860"}}
